You‚Äôre welcome, I‚Äôm in the same boat as you. I‚Äôm trying to stay positive. I‚Äôve seen your past posts and it reminds me of my thoughts every day. Keep your head up! Everything will be okay. I know things seem hard and difficult right now but focus on the positives. Think of all that you do have that you are thankful for (roof over your head, family, job, pets, plenty of food) I know it seems stupid but putting things into perspective really helps me. Always knowing that there is someone out there that has it worse than me makes me thankful that what I consider is a big deal to me can be so small in the grand scheme of things. I know that you can‚Äôt see a doctor right now but have you ever thought about online therapy? I know a lot of therapist are conducting online therapy sessions, maybe reach out to your doctor over the phone and ask if he/she knows of any in your area... if not a good google search might point you in the right direction! Keep your mind busy, get some exercise (if you can), talk to your friends and family, take up a hobby, read a book. I notice that when my mind is busy I forget about my troubles and things that are bothering me. No matter what,  just know you aren‚Äôt alone and so many people are struggling. Be strong you WILL get through this. Just keep saying that to yourself when ever you doubt it.

I seem to have the same issue as you, insomnia, anxiety, depression. My dr gave me multiple different sleeping pills to try and even at the highest doses they won‚Äôt knock me out! ‚Äîscary... However, I started exercising, I walk, jog, and so something physical everyday to physically exhaust myself. I find this has helped me a lot. I‚Äôm not saying every time it will work but it‚Äôs been a lot better for me with regular exercise, less sugar, and caffeine in my diet. Also, I suggest listening to a podcast you‚Äôre interested in. I listen to history podcasts and just zone out and close my eyes and eventually I find myself drifting off... don‚Äôt over thing it just let your body relax. Try to limit the screen time on your phone and computer before you go to sleep as well, I find playing video games before bed makes it hard for me to get to sleep. I wish you the best of luck! You‚Äôre young you should be enjoying and sleeping a lot at your age!

I started lexapro after using celixa. I like lexapro a lot more than lexapro, keeps me very calm for the most part... however I don‚Äôt feel that it works well with my anxiety, I‚Äôve been on lexapro for over a year and my depression is a whole lot better and a lot less side effects (pretty much none that I‚Äôm aware of) where as on celixa I was experiencing some annoying side effects. I hope that lexapro works for you and your anxiety, in my experience the best medicine for anxiety is learning valuable coping skills and breathing techniques that will make you stronger mentally. So if this doesn‚Äôt work don‚Äôt be discouraged! You are strong and you WILL get though this. I wish you the best luck, keep us updated (:

When you are in  computer science you struggle with the same people for years getting through the difficulties of the major. I have learned so much from my class mates that I would never know if i didn‚Äôt work so closely with all of them. Yes I know that there are people who don‚Äôt come out and say it, but I also know that there are people that bring up their lives outside of school in which we all do because we are all friends getting through this together. People from all walks of live, races, and views. I‚Äôve learned a lot about my class mates and we even confide in each other when we have issues going on outside of school. I have a close bond with a lot of students in my major. So on the contrary I think they would talk about it. It‚Äôs 2019 almost 2020 and we go to a liberal arts school in which LGBT people are more than welcomed and accepted.

I‚Äôve never met a LGBT person throughout my years of computer science, I do however seen kids and adults that struggle with social settings and are socially awkward. I‚Äôm guessing a lot of people were considered ‚Äúnerds‚Äù in high school because they were good with or liked computers so they spent time at home a lot in high school and college playing around with them.

If you are excited about learning computer science and bad at math thats fine, just know that there are prerequisites that you need in order to take upper level computer science courses... however this varies by school. For example my school offers an alternative program that is based more on the computer science aspect and does not require many general education requirements such as physics, chemistry, and higher level math courses. Im not strong at math but I was able to get through calc 1 and discrete math without much of an issue. if you apply yourself and take use of campus resources like tutors, study groups, and office hours with the professor then you will be just fine.
